tivity}}\n\n[[Category:Exact solutions in general relativity]]\n[[Category:Black holes]]\n[[Category:1916 in science]]\n", "name_user": "Bomb319", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarzschild_metric"}
{"title_page": "The Mysterians", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Mysterians (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|text=the ''Captain Scarlet'' episode \"[[The Mysterons]]\"}}\n{{for|the 60s rock group|Question Mark & the Mysterians}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Mysterians\n| image = mysteriansjap.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Japanese theatrical poster for ''The Mysterians''\n| film name = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} -->\n| director = [[Ishir\u014d Honda]]\n| producer = [[Tomoyuki Tanaka]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| writer = \n| screenplay = [[Takeshi Kimura]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| story = Jojiro Okami{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| based on = {{Based on|An adaptation|Shigeru Kayama{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}}}\n| starring = {{plainlist|*[[Kenji Sahara]]\n*[[Yumi Shirakawa]]\n*[[Takashi Shimura]]}}\n| music = [[Akira Ifukube]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| cinematography = Hajime Koizumi{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| editing = Hiroichi Iwashita{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| studio = [[Toho]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}}\n| distributor = <!-- or: | distributors = -->\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|1957|12|28|Japan}}\n| runtime = 89 minutes{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}}\n| country = Japan\n| language = \n| budget = \n| gross =  \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''The Mysterians'''''|\u5730\u7403\u9632\u885b\u8ecd|'''''Chiky\u016b B\u014deigun'''''|lit. Earth Defense Force}} is a 1957 Japanese [[science fiction]] film directed by [[Ishir\u014d Honda]] and stars [[Kenji Sahara]], [[Yumi Shirakawa]] and [[Takashi Shimura]]. The film begins with a giant fissure destroying an entire village. This leads to an investigation whereby the source is discovered to be Moguera, a giant robot, who is then destroyed by the military. The remains are analyzed and discovered to be of alien origin. Shortly after, an alien race known as the Mysterians arrive, declaring they have taken some Earth women captive and that they demand both land and the right to marry women of Earth.\n\nFor ''The Mysterians'', producer [[Tomoyuki Tanaka]] recruited [[Jojiro Okami]], a science fiction writer, to develop the story. Honda later elaborated that he wanted the film to differ from both ''[[Godzilla (1954 film)|Godzilla]]'' and ''[[Rodan (film)|Rodan]]'' and to make it more of a \"true science fiction film,\" one to promote peace and understanding between cultures. The film was popular upon its release in Japan, where it was among the top ten grossing domestic productions of the year. Contemporary reviews from Western critics in the ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' and ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the special effect work but criticized the plot as confusing and juvenile, respectively.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Astrophysicist]] Ryoichi Shiraishi, his fiancee Hiroko, his sister Etsuko, and his friend Joji Atsumi attend a festival at a local village near [[Mount Fuji]]. Shiraishi then tells Atsumi that he has broken off his engagement with Hiroko but gives no reason other than an undisclosed obligation to remain in the village. Then, a  mysterious forest fire flares up, burning more rapidly than normal and emanating from the ground, and Shiraishi rushes out to investigate and disappears during the confusion.\n\nThe next day, Atsumi is at the local observatory, where he meets with his mentor, head [[astronomer]], Tanjiro Adachi. He hands the doctor a report written by Shiraishi that concerns a newly discovered [[asteroid]] that Shiraishi theorized was once a planet between [[Mars]] and [[Jupiter]]. He has named it Mysteroid. However, Adachi does not believe in his radical theory and also points out that the report is not complete.\n\nMeanwhile, the village in which the festival was held is completely wiped out by a massive [[earthquake]]. While investigating the area, Atsumi and a group of police officers stumble upon a giant robot, [[Moguera]], which bursts from the side of a hill. It emits rays which decimate the investigation team; only Atsumi and the lead policeman survive. The robot then advances to a town near Koyama Bridge that night, and is met by heavy resistance from Japan's self-defense force. However, the conventional artillery has no effect on the war machine, and the automaton continues its rampage until it tries to cross the Koyama Bridge, which is detonated, sending the machine crashing down to the ground below and destroying it.\n\nAt the [[Diet Building]], Atsumi briefs officials on what has been learned about the robot. The remains of the giant machine reveal that it was manufactured out of an unknown chemical compound. Shortly afterwards, astronomers witness activity in outer space around the moon. They alert the world to this discovery, and not long after, the aliens emerge, their gigantic dome breaking through Earth's crust near Mount Fuji.\n\nAs a combined military and scientific entourage observes the dome, a voice calls out to request five scientists, including Dr. Adachi, who is among the observers, to come to the dome for a conference. The men agree to this meeting and are formally ushered into the dome, where the Mysterians, a scientifically advanced humanoid alien race, list their demands from the people of Earth: a two-mile-radius strip of land and the right to marry women of Earth. The reason for this is that 100,000 years ago their planet&mdash;Mysteroid, once the [[Planet V|fifth planet from the sun]]&mdash;was destroyed by a nuclear war. Some Mysterians were able to escape to Mars before their planet was rendered uninhabitable. However, owing to the nuclear war, Strontium-90 has left 80&nbsp;percent of the aliens' population deformed and crippled. The proposed interbreeding with women on Earth would produce healthier offspring and keep their race alive. The latter part of their demands is downplayed, as they admit to already taking three women captive and reveal two others that they are interested in, one of which is Etsuko.\n\nJapan quickly dismisses this request and begins the mobilization of its armed forces around [[Mount Fuji]]. It is also discovered that the missing Shiraishi has sided with the advance race because of their technological achievements. Japan wastes no time, though, and quickly launches a full-scale attack against the Mysterians' dome. However, the modern weaponry is no match for their technology, and Japan's forces are easily fought back. Distraught by this setback, Japan sends their plea to other nations that they join together to remove the threat of the Mysterians from Earth. The nations around the world answer the plea and in no time issue another raid against the Mysterians' dome, this time utilizing the newly developed Alpha and Beta class airships. Sadly, this attack meets failure as well.\n\nThe Mysterians then increase their demand, asking for a 75-mile-radius plot of land, as the Earth continues to develop a new method of attack. Earth's efforts in this matter pay off as a Markalite FAHP (Flying Atomic Heat Projector), a gigantic lens that can reflect the Mysterians\u2019 weaponry, is designed. Meanwhile, the Mysterians kidnap Etsuko and Hiroko, causing Atsumi to search for, and locate, a cave entrance to a tunnel under the Mysterians' dome.\n\nIn the meantime, the Markalite FAHP's are deployed by large Markalite GYRO rockets, and the final battle against the Mysterians' base of operations commences. Atsumi enters the dome and finds the women, alive and unharmed, in an unguarded room. Taking them back to the tunnel, Atsumi finds Shiraishi, who admits the Mysterians duped him and have no good intentions, and then returns to the dome and sacrifices himself in a final attack on the base from the inside while the Markalite FAHP's assault the base from above ground. The dome collapses and then explodes as Adachi and the women reach safety in the hills above the Mysterians' occupied land. A few enemy spaceships are observed fleeing into space, out of range of Earth weaponry, and Dr. Adachi comments on the need for continued vigilance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Kenji Sahara]] as J\u014dji Atsumi\n*[[Yumi Shirakawa]] as Etsuko Shiraishi\n*[[Momoko K\u014dchi]] as Hiroko Iwamoto\n*[[Akihiko Hirata]] as Ry\u014dichi Shiraishi\n*[[Takashi Shimura]] as Dr. Kenjir\u014d Adachi\n*[[Susumu Fujita]] as General Morita\n*[[Hisaya It\u014d]] as Captain Seki\n*[[Yoshio Kosugi]] as Commander Sugimoto\n*[[Fuyuki Murakami]] as Dr. Nobu Kawanami\n*[[Tetsu Nakamura (actor)|Tetsu Nakamura]] as Dr. K\u014dda\n*[[Yoshio Tsuchiya]] as Mysterian Leader\n\n==Production==\nDirector Ishiro Honda described the film, saying it was \"larger in scale compared to ''Godzilla'' or ''Rodan'' and is aimed to be more of a true science fiction film&nbsp;... I would like to wipe away the [Cold War-era] notion of East versus West and convey a simple, universal aspiration for peace, the coming together of all humankind as one to create a peaceful society.\"{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=137}} For ''The Mysterians'', producer [[Tomoyuki Tanaka]] recruited [[Jojiro Okami]], an aeronautical engineer and military test pilot who later became a science fiction writer.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=139}} Reflecting on the period of developing the film, Honda stated that he respected scientists, but \"feared the danger of science, that whoever controlled it could take over the entire Earth.\"{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=139}} \n\n''The Mysterians'' marks the first collaboration between Honda and special effects director [[Eiji Tsuburaya]] that was shot in anamorphic [[Tohoscope]], which the studio had just recently introduced.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=139}} In their book on Honda, Ryfle and Godziszewski stated that accurate budget figures for ''The Mysterians'' are elusive.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=140}} Honda had stated that the film was more expensive than ''Godzilla'' and ''Rodan''.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=140}}\n\n==Release==\n''The Mysterians'' was released in 28 December 1957 in Japan.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}} The film was re-issued theatrically in Japan on 18 March 1978.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=311}} The film was described by Ryfle and Godziszewski as a \"significant hit\", earning 193 million yen in the domestic box office. It was Toho's second highest grossing film of the year, only being behind [[Hiroshi Inagaki]]'s ''[[Rickshaw Man]]'', and was the tenth highest grossing film in Japan overall.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=141}} \n\nIn the United States, ''The Mysterians'' was originally purchased by [[RKO Pictures|RKO Radio Pictures]], which provided the dubbing, but was sold to [[Loew's Inc.]] for release due to RKO's failing fortunes.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}} The film was double-billed with ''[[Watusi (film)|Watusi]]'' and released in 15 May 1959 via [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}}  According to MGM records the film made the studio a profit of only $58,000 in the United States.<ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation | title = The Eddie Mannix Ledger | publisher = Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study | place = Los Angeles}}.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nFrom contemporary reviews, ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the film \"an ear-splitting Japanese-made fantasy, photographed in runny color and dubbed English,\" and concluded: \"This Metro release is crammed with routine footage of death rays and scrambling civilians, not one of whom can act.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news \n  | author = H.H.T.\n  | title = Screen: A Double Bill; ' Watusi' Arrives With 'The Mysterians'\n  | work = [[The New York Times]]\n  | date =July 2, 1959\n  | accessdate= December 20, 2016\n  | url =https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D03E7D8173BEF3BBC4A53DFB1668382649EDE&scp=2&sq=mysterians&st=cse\n  }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"well-produced\", noting \"special effects involving sliding land, quaking earth and melting mortars are realistically accomplished proving the facility with the Japanese filmmakers deal in miniatures.\"{{sfn|Willis|1985|p=138|ps=: \"Reviewed on May 15, 1959\"}} but found the film \"As corny as it is furious\" noting that \"While Junior may be moved by the arrival of outer-space gremlins, big brother and all like him will laugh their heads off.\"{{sfn|Willis|1985|p=138|ps=: \"Reviewed on May 15, 1959\"}} The review commented on the English dub, stating that it was \"understandable enough, but one might easily believe something was lost in translation.\"{{sfn|Willis|1985|p=138|ps=: \"Reviewed on May 15, 1959\"}} [[Harrison's Reports]] wrote that the film is \"far better than most American-made pictures of its type\" and \"\"although the story idea offers little that is novel, the action holds one's interest well mainly because of the imaginative settings, the elaborate space ship used by the invaders along with its many electronic gadgets, and the very good special effects by which catastrophic scenes of destruction are depicted while the invaders and the Earthians battle each other [with] all sorts of weapons.\" <ref name=\"hr\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Harrison's Reports]]|title=Chikyu Boeigun (The Mysterians), Japan, 1957|page=83|volume=41|issue=21|year=1959|publisher=[[Harrison's Reports, Inc.]]}}</ref> \n\nThe ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' noted that the version the reviewer viewed was a \"banal American-dubbed version\" and that its \"main weaknesses are a slight and confused plot, under-developed characterisation and artless acting;\"<ref name=\"mfb\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]|title=Chikyu Boeigun (The Mysterians), Japan, 1957|page=58|volume=26|issue=300|year=1959|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref> The review praised the film's \"imaginative art direction and spectacular staging\" which the review stated as \"possibly the most dazzling display of pyrotechnics in the ''genre'' to date.\"<ref name=\"mfb\" /> [[Motion Picture Daily]] praised the film's effects, writing that \"even the most jaded action fan will have to admit that some of the scenes of mass catastrophes, the seemingly endless sky and ground skirmishes and the ultra-modern 'Buck Rogers' settings have seldom, if ever, been equalled.\" <ref name=\"mpd\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Motion Picture Daily]]|title=Chikyu Boeigun (The Mysterians), Japan, 1957|page=5|volume=85|issue=95|year=1959|publisher=[[Quigley Publishing Co.]]}}</ref> \n\nIn a retrospective on Soviet science fiction film, British director [[Alex Cox]] compared ''The Mysterians'' to ''[[First Spaceship on Venus]]'' but described the latter as \"more complex and morally ambiguous.\"<ref name=\"Cox 2011\">{{cite web|first1=Alex|last1=Cox|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jun/30/russian-science-fiction-sci-fi-films-bfi|title=Rockets from Russia: great Eastern Bloc science-fiction films|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=June 30, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> [[AllMovie]] praises the film for its special effects.<ref name=\"allmovie\">{{cite web\n  | last = Mannikka\n  | first = Eleanor\n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = The Mysterians\n  | work = [[Allmovie]]\n  | publisher = \n  | date = \n  | url = http://www.allmovie.com/work/the-mysterians-34163\n  | format = \n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2009-07-17}}</ref> In a retrospective review, ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' found that \"Its space-age visuals and colourful design anticipate the spectacular fantasies Honda would go on to make for Toho in the [1960s], including Mothra, Godzilla vs. The Thing, Ghidrah The Three-Headed Monster and Invasion of the Astro-Monsters.\"<ref name=\"ss-review\">{{citation |title=Reviews: DVDs: Close-Up: Origins of the Species|last=Hollings|first=Ken|magazine=[[Sight and Sound]]|date=March 2006|volume=16|issue=3|page=92|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=The Japanese Filmography: 1900 through 1994 |publisher=McFarland |date=1996 |isbn=0-7864-0032-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=The Toho Studios Story: A History and Complete Filmography |publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=2008 |isbn=1461673747 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ryfle|first1=Steve|last2=Godziszewski|first2=Ed|title=Ishiro Honda: A Life in Film, from Godzilla to Kurosawa|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|year=2017|isbn=9780819570871|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n |editor-last=Willis\n |editor-first=Donald\n |title=Variety's Complete Science Fiction Reviews\n |publisher=Garland Publishing Inc.\n |isbn=0-8240-6263-9\n |year=1985\n |ref=harv\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Japanese films of 1957]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.jmdb.ne.jp/1957/cg005010.htm|title=\u5730\u7403\u9632\u885b\u8ecd (Chiky\u016b B\u014deigun)|accessdate=2007-07-13|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Japanese Movie Database]]}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0050251}}\n* {{Amg movie|34163|The Mysterians}}\n* {{tcmdb title|84435|The Mysterians}}\n\n{{Godzilla}}\n{{Ishir\u014d Honda}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mysterians, The}}\n[[Category:1950s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Akira Ifukube]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ishir\u014d Honda]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Tomoyuki Tanaka]]\n[[Category:Films set in Shizuoka Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tochigi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films set in Yamanashi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Kaiju films]]\n[[Category:1950s monster movies]]\n[[Category:Robot films]]\n[[Category:Toho tokusatsu films]]\n[[Category:Alien invasions in films]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Mysterians (disambiguation)}}\n{{distinguish|text=the ''Captain Scarlet'' episode \"[[The Mysterons]]\"}}\n{{for|the 60s rock group|Question Mark & the Mysterians}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = The Mysterians\n| image = mysteriansjap.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Japanese theatrical poster for ''The Mysterians''\n| film name = <!-- {{Infobox name module|language|title}} or {{Infobox name module|title}} -->\n| director = [[Ishir\u014d Honda]]\n| producer = [[Tomoyuki Tanaka]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| writer = \n| screenplay = [[Takeshi Kimura]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| story = Jojiro Okami{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| based on = {{Based on|An adaptation|Shigeru Kayama{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}}}\n| starring = {{plainlist|*[[Kenji Sahara]]\n*[[Yumi Shirakawa]]\n*[[Takashi Shimura]]}}\n| music = [[Akira Ifukube]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| cinematography = Hajime Koizumi{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| editing = Hiroichi Iwashita{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=301}}\n| studio = [[Toho]]{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}}\n| distributor = <!-- or: | distributors = -->\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|1957|12|28|Japan}}\n| runtime = 89 minutes{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}}\n| country = Japan\n| language = \n| budget = \n| gross =  \n}}\n{{nihongo|'''''The Mysterians'''''|\u5730\u7403\u9632\u885b\u8ecd|'''''Chiky\u016b B\u014deigun'''''|lit. Earth Defense Force}} is a 1957 Japanese [[science fiction]] film directed by [[Ishir\u014d Honda]] and stars [[Kenji Sahara]], [[Yumi Shirakawa]] and [[Takashi Shimura]]. The film begins with a giant fissure destroying an entire village. This leads to an investigation whereby the source is discovered to be Moguera, a giant robot, who is then destroyed by the military. The remains are analyzed and discovered to be of alien origin. Shortly after, an alien race known as the Mysterians arrive, declaring they have taken some Earth women captive and that they demand both land and the right to marry women of Earth.\n\nFor ''The Mysterians'', producer [[Tomoyuki Tanaka]] recruited [[Jojiro Okami]], a science fiction writer, to develop the story. Honda later elaborated that he wanted the film to differ from both ''[[Godzilla (1954 film)|Godzilla]]'' and ''[[Rodan (film)|Rodan]]'' and to make it more of a \"true science fiction film,\" one to promote peace and understanding between cultures. The film was popular upon its release in Japan, where it was among the top ten grossing domestic productions of the year. Contemporary reviews from Western critics in the ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' and ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' praised the special effect work but criticized the plot as confusing and juvenile, respectively.\n\n==Plot==\n[[Astrophysicist]] Ryoichi Shiraishi, his fiancee Hiroko, his sister Etsuko, and his friend Joji Atsumi attend a festival at a local village near [[Mount Fuji]]. Shiraishi then tells Atsumi that he has broken off his engagement with Hiroko but gives no reason other than an undisclosed obligation to remain in the village. Then, a  mysterious forest fire flares up, burning more rapidly than normal and emanating from the ground, and Shiraishi rushes out to investigate and disappears during the confusion.\n\nThe next day, Atsumi is at the local observatory, where he meets with his mentor, head [[astronomer]], Tanjiro Adachi. He hands the doctor a report written by Shiraishi that concerns a newly discovered [[asteroid]] that Shiraishi theorized was once a planet between [[Mars]] and [[Jupiter]]. He has named it Mysteroid. However, Adachi does not believe in his radical theory and also points out that the report is not complete.\n\nMeanwhile, the village in which the festival was held is completely wiped out by a massive [[earthquake]]. While investigating the area, Atsumi and a group of police officers stumble upon a giant robot, [[Moguera]], which bursts from the side of a hill. It emits rays which decimate the investigation team; only Atsumi and the lead policeman survive. The robot then advances to a town near Koyama Bridge that night, and is met by heavy resistance from Japan's self-defense force. However, the conventional artillery has no effect on the war machine, and the automaton continues its rampage until it tries to cross the Koyama Bridge, which is detonated, sending the machine crashing down to the ground below and destroying it.\n\nAt the [[Diet Building]], Atsumi briefs officials on what has been learned about the robot. The remains of the giant machine reveal that it was manufactured out of an unknown chemical compound. Shortly afterwards, astronomers witness activity in outer space around the moon. They alert the world to this discovery, and not long after, the aliens emerge, their gigantic dome breaking through Earth's crust near Mount Fuji.\n\nAs a combined military and scientific entourage observes the dome, a voice calls out to request five scientists, including Dr. Adachi, who is among the observers, to come to the dome for a conference. The men agree to this meeting and are formally ushered into the dome, where the Mysterians, a scientifically advanced humanoid alien race, list their demands from the people of Earth: a two-mile-radius strip of land and the right to marry women of Earth. The reason for this is that 100,000 years ago their planet&mdash;Mysteroid, once the [[Planet V|fifth planet from the sun]]&mdash;was destroyed by a nuclear war. Some Mysterians were able to escape to Mars before their planet was rendered uninhabitable. However, owing to the nuclear war, Strontium-90 has left 80&nbsp;percent of the aliens' population deformed and crippled. The proposed interbreeding with women on Earth would produce healthier offspring and keep their race alive. The latter part of their demands is downplayed, as they admit to already taking three women captive and reveal two others that they are interested in, one of which is Etsuko.\n\nJapan quickly dismisses this request and begins the mobilization of its armed forces around [[Mount Fuji]]. It is also discovered that the missing Shiraishi has sided with the advance race because of their technological achievements. Japan wastes no time, though, and quickly launches a full-scale attack against the Mysterians' dome. However, the modern weaponry is no match for their technology, and Japan's forces are easily fought back. Distraught by this setback, Japan sends their plea to other nations that they join together to remove the threat of the Mysterians from Earth. The nations around the world answer the plea and in no time issue another raid against the Mysterians' dome, this time utilizing the newly developed Alpha and Beta class airships. Sadly, this attack meets failure as well.\n\nThe Mysterians then increase their demand, asking for a 75-mile-radius plot of land, as the Earth continues to develop a new method of attack. Earth's efforts in this matter pay off as a Markalite FAHP (Flying Atomic Heat Projector), a gigantic lens that can reflect the Mysterians\u2019 weaponry, is designed. Meanwhile, the Mysterians kidnap Etsuko and Hiroko, causing Atsumi to search for, and locate, a cave entrance to a tunnel under the Mysterians' dome.\n\nIn the meantime, the Markalite FAHP's are deployed by large Markalite GYRO rockets, and the final battle against the Mysterians' base of operations commences. Atsumi enters the dome and finds the women, alive and unharmed, in an unguarded room. Taking them back to the tunnel, Atsumi finds Shiraishi, who admits the Mysterians duped him and have no good intentions, and then returns to the dome and sacrifices himself in a final attack on the base from the inside while the Markalite FAHP's assault the base from above ground. The dome collapses and then explodes as Adachi and the women reach safety in the hills above the Mysterians' occupied land. A few enemy spaceships are observed fleeing into space, out of range of Earth weaponry, and Dr. Adachi comments on the need for continued vigilance.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Kenji Sahara]] as J\u014dji Atsumi\n*[[Yumi Shirakawa]] as Etsuko Shiraishi\n*[[Momoko K\u014dchi]] as Hiroko Iwamoto\n*[[Akihiko Hirata]] as Ry\u014dichi Shiraishi\n*[[Takashi Shimura]] as Dr. Kenjir\u014d Adachi\n*[[Susumu Fujita]] as General Morita\n*[[Hisaya It\u014d]] as Captain Seki\n*[[Yoshio Kosugi]] as Commander Sugimoto\n*[[Fuyuki Murakami]] as Dr. Nobu Kawanami\n*[[Tetsu Nakamura (actor)|Tetsu Nakamura]] as Dr. K\u014dda\n*[[Yoshio Tsuchiya]] as Mysterian Leader\n\n==Production==\nDirector Ishiro Honda described the film, saying it was \"larger in scale compared to ''Godzilla'' or ''Rodan'' and is aimed to be more of a true science fiction film&nbsp;... I would like to wipe away the [Cold War-era] notion of East versus West and convey a simple, universal aspiration for peace, the coming together of all humankind as one to create a peaceful society.\"{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=137}} For ''The Mysterians'', producer [[Tomoyuki Tanaka]] recruited [[Jojiro Okami]], an aeronautical engineer and military test pilot who later became a science fiction writer.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=139}} Reflecting on the period of developing the film, Honda stated that he respected scientists, but \"feared the danger of science, that whoever controlled it could take over the entire Earth.\"{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=139}} \n\n''The Mysterians'' marks the first collaboration between Honda and special effects director [[Eiji Tsuburaya]] that was shot in anamorphic [[Tohoscope]], which the studio had just recently introduced.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=139}} In their book on Honda, Ryfle and Godziszewski stated that accurate budget figures for ''The Mysterians'' are elusive.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=140}} Honda had stated that the film was more expensive than ''Godzilla'' and ''Rodan''.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=140}}\n\n==Release==\n''The Mysterians'' was released in 28 December 1957 in Japan.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}} The film was re-issued theatrically in Japan on 18 March 1978.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|2008|p=311}} The film was described by Ryfle and Godziszewski as a \"significant hit\", earning 193 million yen in the domestic box office. It was Toho's second highest grossing film of the year, only being behind [[Hiroshi Inagaki]]'s ''[[Rickshaw Man]]'', and was the tenth highest grossing film in Japan overall.{{sfn|Ryfle|Godziszewski|2017|p=141}} \n\nIn the United States, ''The Mysterians'' was originally purchased by [[RKO Pictures|RKO Radio Pictures]], which provided the dubbing, but was sold to [[Loew's Inc.]] for release due to RKO's failing fortunes.{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}} The film was double-billed with ''[[Watusi (film)|Watusi]]'' and released in 15 May 1959 via [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer|MGM]].{{sfn|Galbraith IV|1996|p=302}}  According to MGM records the film made the studio a profit of only $58,000 in the United States.<ref name=\"Mannix\">{{Citation | title = The Eddie Mannix Ledger | publisher = Margaret Herrick Library, Center for Motion Picture Study | place = Los Angeles}}.</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nFrom contemporary reviews, ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the film \"an ear-splitting Japanese-made fantasy, photographed in runny color and dubbed English,\" and concluded: \"This Metro release is crammed with routine footage of death rays and scrambling civilians, not one of whom can act.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news \n  | author = H.H.T.\n  | title = Screen: A Double Bill; ' Watusi' Arrives With 'The Mysterians'\n  | work = [[The New York Times]]\n  | date =July 2, 1959\n  | accessdate= December 20, 2016\n  | url =https://www.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9D03E7D8173BEF3BBC4A53DFB1668382649EDE&scp=2&sq=mysterians&st=cse\n  }}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"well-produced\", noting \"special effects involving sliding land, quaking earth and melting mortars are realistically accomplished proving the facility with the Japanese filmmakers deal in miniatures.\"{{sfn|Willis|1985|p=138|ps=: \"Reviewed on May 15, 1959\"}} but found the film \"As corny as it is furious\" noting that \"While Junior may be moved by the arrival of outer-space gremlins, big brother and all like him will laugh their heads off.\"{{sfn|Willis|1985|p=138|ps=: \"Reviewed on May 15, 1959\"}} The review commented on the English dub, stating that it was \"understandable enough, but one might easily believe something was lost in translation.\"{{sfn|Willis|1985|p=138|ps=: \"Reviewed on May 15, 1959\"}} [[Harrison's Reports]] wrote that the film is \"far better than most American-made pictures of its type\" and \"\"although the story idea offers little that is novel, the action holds one's interest well mainly because of the imaginative settings, the elaborate space ship used by the invaders along with its many electronic gadgets, and the very good special effects by which catastrophic scenes of destruction are depicted while the invaders and the Earthians battle each other [with] all sorts of weapons.\" <ref name=\"hr\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Harrison's Reports]]|title=Chikyu Boeigun (The Mysterians), Japan, 1957|page=83|volume=41|issue=21|year=1959|publisher=[[Harrison's Reports, Inc.]]}}</ref> \n\nThe ''[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]'' noted that the version the reviewer viewed was a \"banal American-dubbed version\" and that its \"main weaknesses are a slight and confused plot, under-developed characterisation and artless acting;\"<ref name=\"mfb\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Monthly Film Bulletin]]|title=Chikyu Boeigun (The Mysterians), Japan, 1957|page=58|volume=26|issue=300|year=1959|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref> The review praised the film's \"imaginative art direction and spectacular staging\" which the review stated as \"possibly the most dazzling display of pyrotechnics in the ''genre'' to date.\"<ref name=\"mfb\" /> [[Motion Picture Daily]] praised the film's effects, writing that \"even the most jaded action fan will have to admit that some of the scenes of mass catastrophes, the seemingly endless sky and ground skirmishes and the ultra-modern 'Buck Rogers' settings have seldom, if ever, been equalled.\" <ref name=\"mpd\">{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Motion Picture Daily]]|title=Chikyu Boeigun (The Mysterians), Japan, 1957|page=5|volume=85|issue=95|year=1959|publisher=[[Quigley Publishing Co.]]}}</ref> \n\nIn a retrospective on Soviet science fiction film, British director [[Alex Cox]] compared ''The Mysterians'' to ''[[First Spaceship on Venus]]'' but described the latter as \"more complex and morally ambiguous.\"<ref name=\"Cox 2011\">{{cite web|first1=Alex|last1=Cox|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/jun/30/russian-science-fiction-sci-fi-films-bfi|title=Rockets from Russia: great Eastern Bloc science-fiction films|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=June 30, 2011|accessdate=August 22, 2016}}</ref> [[AllMovie]] praises the film for its special effects.<ref name=\"allmovie\">{{cite web\n  | last = Mannikka\n  | first = Eleanor\n  | authorlink = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = The Mysterians\n  | work = [[Allmovie]]\n  | publisher = \n  | date = \n  | url = http://www.allmovie.com/work/the-mysterians-34163\n  | format = \n  | doi = \n  | accessdate = 2009-07-17}}</ref> In a retrospective review, ''[[Sight & Sound]]'' found that \"Its space-age visuals and colourful design anticipate the spectacular fantasies Honda would go on to make for Toho in the [1960s], including Mothra, Godzilla vs. The Thing, Ghidrah The Three-Headed Monster and Invasion of the Astro-Monsters.\"<ref name=\"ss-review\">{{cite web|title=Reviews: DVDs: Close-Up: Origins of the Species|last=Hollings|first=Ken|magazine=[[Sight and Sound]]|date=March 2006|volume=16|issue=3|page=92|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=The Japanese Filmography: 1900 through 1994 |publisher=McFarland |date=1996 |isbn=0-7864-0032-3 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Galbraith IV |first=Stuart |title=The Toho Studios Story: A History and Complete Filmography |publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=2008 |isbn=1461673747 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Ryfle|first1=Steve|last2=Godziszewski|first2=Ed|title=Ishiro Honda: A Life in Film, from Godzilla to Kurosawa|publisher=Wesleyan University Press|year=2017|isbn=9780819570871|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book\n |editor-last=Willis\n |editor-first=Donald\n |title=Variety's Complete Science Fiction Reviews\n |publisher=Garland Publishing Inc.\n |isbn=0-8240-6263-9\n |year=1985\n |ref=harv\n}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Japanese films of 1957]]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.jmdb.ne.jp/1957/cg005010.htm|title=\u5730\u7403\u9632\u885b\u8ecd (Chiky\u016b B\u014deigun)|accessdate=2007-07-13|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Japanese Movie Database]]}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0050251}}\n* {{Amg movie|34163|The Mysterians}}\n* {{tcmdb title|84435|The Mysterians}}\n\n{{Godzilla}}\n{{Ishir\u014d Honda}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mysterians, The}}\n[[Category:1950s science fiction films]]\n[[Category:1957 films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Akira Ifukube]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Ishir\u014d Honda]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Tomoyuki Tanaka]]\n[[Category:Films set in Shizuoka Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tochigi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Films set in Tokyo]]\n[[Category:Films set in Yamanashi Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Japanese films]]\n[[Category:Japanese-language films]]\n[[Category:Kaiju films]]\n[[Category:1950s monster movies]]\n[[Category:Robot films]]\n[[Category:Toho tokusatsu films]]\n[[Category:Alien invasions in films]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Mysterians"}
{"title_page": "Jo\u00e3o Pereira (footballer, born 1990)", "text_new": "{{For|other people named Jo\u00e3o Pereira|Jo\u00e3o Pereira (disambiguation){{!}}Jo\u00e3o Pereira}}\n{{portuguese name|Vieira|Pereira}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Jo\u00e3o Pereira\n|image =\n|fullname = Jo\u00e3o Duarte Vieira Pereira\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|5|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Cartaxo]], [[Portugal]]\n|height = {{height|m=1.83}}\n|position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n|currentclub = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]]\n|clubnumber = 14\n|youthyears1 = 2001\u20132004 | youthclubs1 = SL Cartaxo\n|youthyears2 = 2004\u20132009 | youthclubs2 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n|years1 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs1 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0\n|years2 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[C.D. F\u00e1tima|F\u00e1tima]] (loan) | caps2 = 48 | goals2 = 2\n|years3 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs3 = [[S.C. Beira-Mar|Beira-Mar]] | caps3 = 0 | goals3 = 0\n|years4 = 2011  | clubs4 = \u2192 [[C.D. Trofense|Trofense]] (loan) | caps4 = 7 | goals4 = 0\n|years5 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs5 = [[FC Sheriff Tiraspol|Sheriff]] | caps5 = 10 | goals5 = 0\n|years6 = 2013 | clubs6 = [[FC Nordsj\u00e6lland|Nordsj\u00e6lland]] | caps6 = 0 | goals6 = 0\n|years7 = 2013\u20132015 | clubs7 = [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle]] | caps7 = 47 | goals7 = 0\n|years8 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs8 = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]] | caps8 = 24 | goals8 = 1\n|years9 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs9 = [[Odense Boldklub|Odense]] | caps9 = 23 | goals9 = 0\n|years10 = 2018\u2013 | clubs10 = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]] | caps10 = 2 | goals10 = 0\n|totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n|nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132006 | nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-16 football team|Portugal U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 2006\u20132007 | nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]] | nationalcaps2 = 8 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3 = 2008 | nationalteam3 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]] | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n|nationalyears4 = 2008\u20132009 | nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal U19]] | nationalcaps4 = 11 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n|nationalyears5 = 2010 | nationalteam5 = [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal U20]] | nationalcaps5 = 4 | nationalgoals5 = 0\n|nationalyears6 = 2011\u20132012 | nationalteam6 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]] | nationalcaps6 = 15 | nationalgoals6 = 1\n|club-update = 22 February 2019\n|nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Jo\u00e3o Duarte Vieira Pereira''' (born 10 May 1990) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for Danish club [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Cartaxo]], [[Santar\u00e9m District]], Pereira started playing football in 2001 at Sport Lisboa e Cartaxo, a subsidiary club of [[S.L. Benfica]]. He represented the former for three years, until he was called up by the latter to finish his formation.\n\nAfter signing a professional contract, Pereira trained with the first team at [[Futebol Campus]] in [[Seixal]], but also in the pre-season tour of [[Nyon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/aguias-remedeiam-ausencia-de-centrais.html|title=\u00c1guias remedeiam aus\u00eancia de centrais|trans-title=Eagles address lack of centre-backs|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=Portuguese|date=10 July 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/convocados-27-jogadores.html|title=Convocados 27 jogadores|trans-title=27 players called up|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=8 July 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> Upon arriving in Switzerland, he was loaned to [[C.D. F\u00e1tima]] for one year,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://serbenfiquista.com/usernews/jo%C3%A3o-pereira-ex-junior-cedido-ao-f%C3%A1rima-por-1-%C3%A9poca|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-junior) cedido ao F\u00e1tima por 1 \u00e9poca|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (former junior) loaned to F\u00e1tima for 1 season|publisher=Ser Benfiquista|language=Portuguese|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> making his professional debut on 20 September by playing the full 90 minutes in a 1\u20132 home loss against [[S.C. Beira-Mar]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/detalhe/fatima---beira-mar-1-2-alguma-sorte-aveirense.html|title=F\u00e1tima \u2013 Beira-Mar, 1\u20132: Alguma sorte aveirense|trans-title=F\u00e1tima \u2013 Beira-Mar, 1\u20132: A bit of luck for the men from Aveiro|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=20 September 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> he appeared in 24 games and scored once in each of his two seasons in the [[Segunda Liga]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/desporto/benfica-empresta-seis-jogadores-ao-cd-fatima=f590319|title=Benfica empresta seis jogadores ao CD F\u00e1tima|trans-title=Benfica loan six players to CD F\u00e1tima|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|language=Portuguese|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> helping to a best-ever eighth place in [[2009\u201310 Liga de Honra|2009\u201310]].\n\nIn June 2011, Pereira opted to terminate his contract with Benfica and sign a two-year deal with Beira-Mar.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://semanal.omirante.pt/index.asp?idEdicao=503&id=75946&idSeccao=8231&Action=noticia#.Vv1QfkcjW1s|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira deixou o Benfica e assinou pelo Beira Mar|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira left Benfica and signed with Beira-Mar|newspaper=O Mirante|language=Portuguese|date=7 July 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/beira-mar-joao-pereira-ex-benfica-e-reforco|title=Beira Mar: Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Benfica) \u00e9 refor\u00e7o|trans-title=Beira-Mar: Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Benfica) is an addition|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=23 June 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> He would never appear for the team in a competitive game, being loaned the following month to [[C.D. Trofense]] also from the second division;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.noticiasdeaveiro.pt/pt/23050/beiramar-central-joao-pereira-vai-rodar-no-trofense/|title=Beira-Mar: Central Jo\u00e3o Pereira vai rodar no Trofense|trans-title=Beira-Mar: Stopper Jo\u00e3o Pereira will gain match experience in Trofense|newspaper=Not\u00edcias de Aveiro|language=Portuguese|date=30 August 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> in December, he agreed to a three-and-a-half-year deal with [[FC Sheriff Tiraspol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/joao-pereira-ex-beira-mar-no-fc-sheriff|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Beira Mar) no FC Sheriff|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Beira Mar) in FC Sheriff|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/beira-mar-confirma-joao-pereira-na-moldavia|title=Beira Mar confirma Jo\u00e3o Pereira na Mold\u00e1via|trans-title=Beira-Mar confirm Jo\u00e3o Pereira in Moldova|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"UEFA\">{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=mda/news/newsid=1785353.html|title=Jovem Jo\u00e3o Pereira espera crescer no Sheriff|trans-title=Youngster Jo\u00e3o Pereira hopes to grow in Sheriff|publisher=UEFA|language=Portuguese|date=17 April 2012|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPereira made his [[Moldovan National Division]] debut on 3 March 2012, playing as [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]] and providing an [[Assist (football)|assist]] in a 2\u20130 away win over [[FC Costuleni]],<ref name=\"UEFA\"/> and going on to contribute to the club's [[2011\u201312 Moldovan National Division|eleventh league title]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/noticia/mais-de-50-portugueses-conquistaram-trofeus-no-futebol-europeu-1548342|title=Mais de 50 portugueses conquistaram trof\u00e9us no futebol europeu|trans-title=Over 50 Portuguese won trophies in European football|newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|language=Portuguese|date=31 May 2012|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> He moved teams in countries again in January 2013, joining [[FC Nordsj\u00e6lland]] from [[Denmark]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://desporto.sapo.mz/futebol/internacional/artigo/2013/01/31/joao-pereira-vai-jogar-para-o-nordsjaelland|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira vai jogar para o Nordsjaelland|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira will play for Nordsjaelland|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=Portuguese|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/feeds/lusa/lusageral/joao-pereira-troca-moldavos-do-sheriff-pelos-dinamarqueses-do-nordsjaelland=f783635|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira troca moldavos do Sheriff pelos dinamarqueses do Nordsjaelland|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira swaps Moldova's Sheriff for Denmark's Nordsjaelland|newspaper=Expresso|language=Portuguese|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> after [[2012\u201313 Moldovan National Division|winning another league medal]] with Sheriff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/internacional/portugueses/noticias/interior/joao-pereira-esta-na-dinamarca-mas-e-campeao-moldavo-3224514.html|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira est\u00e1 na Dinamarca mas \u00e9 campe\u00e3o moldavo|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira is in Denmark but is Moldovan champion|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=Portuguese|date=16 May 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn late August 2013, after failing to receive any playing time, Pereira signed a six-month contract with [[Danish 1st Division|Danish second level]] club [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle BK]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bt.dk/superligaen/vejle-henter-fc-nordsjaellands-kasserede-portugiser|title=Vejle henter FC Nordsj\u00e6llands kasserede portugiser|trans-title=Vejle sign discarded Portuguese from Nordsjaellands|newspaper=[[BT (tabloid)|BT]]|language=Danish|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> He extended his link in November for another six months,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagens.dk/fodbold/jo%C3%A3o-pereira-forl%C3%A6nger-med-vejle-boldklub|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira forl\u00e6nger med Vejle Boldklub|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira renews with Vejle Boldklub|newspaper=Dagens|language=Danish|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> and again in April 2014 for another year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tipsbladet.dk/nyhed/1-division/vejle-forlaenger-med-joao-pereira|title=Vejle forl\u00e6nger med Jo\u00e3o Pereira|trans-title=Vejle renew with Jo\u00e3o Pereira|newspaper=Tipsbladet|language=Danish|date=1 April 2014|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Pereira moved to [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/internacional/artigo/2015/06/26/joao-pereira-assina-pelos-dinamarqueses-do-sonderjyske|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira assina pelos dinamarqueses do SonderjyskE|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira signs for Denmark's SonderjyskE|publisher=SAPO|language=Portuguese|date=26 June 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> In January of the following year, website ''Bold'' announced that fellow [[Danish Superliga]] side [[Odense Boldklub]] had signed him for the [[2016\u201317 Danish Superliga|2016\u201317 campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/ob-bekraefter-henter-joao-pereira/|title=OB bekr\u00e6fter: Henter Joao Pereira|trans-title=Odense deal: Jo\u00e3o Pereira acquired|publisher=Bold|language=Danish|date=26 January 2016|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nPereira earned 49 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], across all youth levels. He played seven times for the [[Portugal national under-16 football team|under\u201316 team]], helping them win the Santar\u00e9m Tournament in February 2006<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-16-ganham-torneio-de-santarem.html|title=Sub-16 ganham Torneio de Santar\u00e9m|trans-title=Under-16 win Santar\u00e9m Tournament|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=28 February 2006|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> and finish seventh in the [[Montaigu Tournament]] in April;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-16-vitoria-sobre-a-china-a-fechar.html|title=Sub-16: Vit\u00f3ria sobre a China a fechar|trans-title=Under-16: Win over China to wrap it up|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=18 April 2006|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> later in the year, he participated in the Nike Tournament with [[Portugal national under-17 football team|the under\u201317s]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-17-portugal-perde-2-4-com-os-eua.html|title=Sub-17: Portugal perde (2\u20134) com os EUA|trans-title=Under-17: Portugal lose 2\u20134 with USA|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=11 September 2006|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> also competing in the Algarve International Tournament in February 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-17-portugal-em-ultimo.html|title=Sub-17: Portugal em \u00faltimo|trans-title=Under-17: Portugal in last place|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=20 February 2007|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPereira represented the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19 team]] during the Ireland Tournament in August 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-derrota-com-a-espanha.html|title=Sub-19: Derrota com a Espanha|trans-title=Under-19: Loss with Spain|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=19 August 2008|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> the La Manga Tournament in February 2009<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-selecao-nacional-conquista-la-manga.html|title=Sub-19: Sele\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional conquista La Manga|trans-title=Under-19: National team conquer La Manga|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=13 February 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> and the Porto Tournament in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-portugal-vence-torneio-internacional-do-porto.html|title=Sub-19: Portugal vence Torneio Internacional do Porto|trans-title=Under-19: Portugal win Porto International Tournament|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=11 April 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> Additionally, he played in the two qualifying rounds for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]], but the nation did not qualify.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-portugal-falha-europeu.html|title=Sub-19: Portugal falha Europeu|trans-title=Under-19: Portugal miss European Championship|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=28 May 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPereira first appeared with [[Portugal national under-21 football team|the under-21 side]] on 9 February 2011, starting in a 3\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win over [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]] in his hometown.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/selecoes/detalhe/sub-21-portugal-bate-suecia-no-cartaxo-683329.html|title=Sub-21: Portugal bate Su\u00e9cia no Cartaxo|trans-title=Under-21: Portugal beat Sweden in Cartaxo|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=9 February 2011|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> His only international goal arrived on 1 September of that year during a 2\u20130 away defeat of [[Moldova national under-21 football team|Moldova]] for the [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|2013 European Championship qualifiers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2013/matches/round=2000192/match=2006904/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Portugal prove too good for Moldova|publisher=UEFA|date=1 September 2011|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref> in which Portugal finished in second thus failing to progress to the finals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/selecoes/sub21/detalhe/avancado-do-v-guimaraes-ajuda-a-afastar-portugal-do-europeu-777549.html|title=Avan\u00e7ado do V. Guimar\u00e3es ajuda a afastar Portugal do Europeu|trans-title=V. Guimar\u00e3es forward helps oust Portugal from the European Championship|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=10 September 2012|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 December 2017}}<ref>{{soccerway|joao-duarte-vieira-pereira/103235}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|National Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|League Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[C.D. F\u00e1tima|F\u00e1tima]]\n|[[2009\u201310 Liga de Honra|2009\u201310]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Segunda Liga]]\n|24||1||0||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||1\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Liga de Honra|2010\u201311]]\n|24||1||0||0||4||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!48!!2!!0!!0!!5!!0!!0!!0!!53!!2\n|-\n|[[C.D. Trofense|Trofense]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Liga de Honra|2011\u201312]]\n|Segunda Liga\n|7||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[FC Sheriff Tiraspol|Sheriff]]\n|[[2011\u201312 Moldovan National Division|2011\u201312]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Moldovan National Division|National Division]]\n|9||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||9||0\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 Moldovan National Division|2012\u201313]]\n|1||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4<ref group=lower-alpha name=\"UCL\">Appearances in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]</ref>||0||5||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!10!!0!!0!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!4!!0!!14!!0\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Danish 1st Division|2013\u201314]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Danish 1st Division|1. Division]]\n|23||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||25||0\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Danish 1st Division|2014\u201315]]\n|24||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||24||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!47!!0!!2!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!0!!0!!49!!0\n|-\n|[[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]]\n|[[2015\u201316 Danish Superliga|2015\u201316]]\n|[[Danish Superliga|Superliga]]\n|24||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||25||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Odense Boldklub|Odense]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Danish Superliga|2016\u201317]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Superliga\n|12||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||12||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Danish Superliga|2017\u201318]]\n|7||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||8||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n!19!!0!!1!!0!!colspan=\"2\"|\u2014!!0!!0!!20!!0\n|-\n!colspan=\"3\"|Career total\n!155!!3!!4!!0!!5!!0!!4!!0!!168!!3\n|}\n\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{ForaDeJogo}}\n* [https://www.fpf.pt/pt/Jogadores/Jogador/playerId/640792 National team data] {{in lang|pt}}\n\n{{S\u00f8nderjyskE squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pereira, Joao}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Portuguese footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:LigaPro players]]\n[[Category:S.L. Benfica footballers]]\n[[Category:C.D. F\u00e1tima players]]\n[[Category:S.C. Beira-Mar players]]\n[[Category:C.D. Trofense players]]\n[[Category:Moldovan National Division players]]\n[[Category:FC Sheriff Tiraspol players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Danish 1st Division players]]\n[[Category:FC Nordsj\u00e6lland players]]\n[[Category:Vejle Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Portugal youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portugal under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Moldova]]\n[[Category:Portuguese expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other people named Jo\u00e3o Pereira|Jo\u00e3o Pereira (disambiguation){{!}}Jo\u00e3o Pereira}}\n{{portuguese name|Vieira|Pereira}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = Jo\u00e3o Pereira\n|image =\n|fullname = Jo\u00e3o Duarte Vieira Pereira\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1990|5|10|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Cartaxo]], [[Portugal]]\n|height = {{height|m=1.83}}\n|position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n|currentclub = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]]\n|clubnumber = 14\n|youthyears1 = 2001\u20132004 | youthclubs1 = SL Cartaxo\n|youthyears2 = 2004\u20132009 | youthclubs2 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]\n|years1 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs1 = [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0\n|years2 = 2009\u20132011 | clubs2 = \u2192 [[C.D. F\u00e1tima|F\u00e1tima]] (loan) | caps2 = 48 | goals2 = 2\n|years3 = 2011\u20132012 | clubs3 = [[S.C. Beira-Mar|Beira-Mar]] | caps3 = 0 | goals3 = 0\n|years4 = 2011  | clubs4 = \u2192 [[C.D. Trofense|Trofense]] (loan) | caps4 = 7 | goals4 = 0\n|years5 = 2012\u20132013 | clubs5 = [[FC Sheriff Tiraspol|Sheriff]] | caps5 = 10 | goals5 = 0\n|years6 = 2013 | clubs6 = [[FC Nordsj\u00e6lland|Nordsj\u00e6lland]] | caps6 = 0 | goals6 = 0\n|years7 = 2013\u20132015 | clubs7 = [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle]] | caps7 = 47 | goals7 = 0\n|years8 = 2015\u20132016 | clubs8 = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]] | caps8 = 24 | goals8 = 1\n|years9 = 2016\u20132018 | clubs9 = [[Odense Boldklub|Odense]] | caps9 = 23 | goals9 = 0\n|years10 = 2018\u2013 | clubs10 = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]] | caps10 = 2 | goals10 = 0\n|totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n|nationalyears1 = 2005\u20132006 | nationalteam1 = [[Portugal national under-16 football team|Portugal U16]] | nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 2006\u20132007 | nationalteam2 = [[Portugal national under-17 football team|Portugal U17]] | nationalcaps2 = 8 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3 = 2008 | nationalteam3 = [[Portugal national under-18 football team|Portugal U18]] | nationalcaps3 = 4 | nationalgoals3 = 0\n|nationalyears4 = 2008\u20132009 | nationalteam4 = [[Portugal national under-19 football team|Portugal U19]] | nationalcaps4 = 11 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n|nationalyears5 = 2010 | nationalteam5 = [[Portugal national under-20 football team|Portugal U20]] | nationalcaps5 = 4 | nationalgoals5 = 0\n|nationalyears6 = 2011\u20132012 | nationalteam6 = [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal U21]] | nationalcaps6 = 15 | nationalgoals6 = 1\n|club-update = 22 February 2019\n|nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Jo\u00e3o Duarte Vieira Pereira''' (born 10 May 1990) is a Portuguese professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for Danish club [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold]] as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Cartaxo]], [[Santar\u00e9m District]], Pereira started playing football in 2001 at Sport Lisboa e Cartaxo, a subsidiary club of [[S.L. Benfica]]. He represented the former for three years, until he was called up by the latter to finish his formation.\n\nAfter signing a professional contract, Pereira trained with the first team at [[Futebol Campus]] in [[Seixal]], but also in the pre-season tour of [[Nyon]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/aguias-remedeiam-ausencia-de-centrais.html|title=\u00c1guias remedeiam aus\u00eancia de centrais|trans-title=Eagles address lack of centre-backs|newspaper=[[Record (newspaper)|Record]]|language=Portuguese|date=10 July 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/liga-nos/benfica/detalhe/convocados-27-jogadores.html|title=Convocados 27 jogadores|trans-title=27 players called up|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=8 July 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> Upon arriving in Switzerland, he was loaned to [[C.D. F\u00e1tima]] for one year,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://serbenfiquista.com/usernews/jo%C3%A3o-pereira-ex-junior-cedido-ao-f%C3%A1rima-por-1-%C3%A9poca|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-junior) cedido ao F\u00e1tima por 1 \u00e9poca|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (former junior) loaned to F\u00e1tima for 1 season|publisher=Ser Benfiquista|language=Portuguese|date=21 July 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> making his professional debut on 20 September by playing the full 90 minutes in a 1\u20132 home loss against [[S.C. Beira-Mar]];<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/futebol-nacional/2--liga/detalhe/fatima---beira-mar-1-2-alguma-sorte-aveirense.html|title=F\u00e1tima \u2013 Beira-Mar, 1\u20132: Alguma sorte aveirense|trans-title=F\u00e1tima \u2013 Beira-Mar, 1\u20132: A bit of luck for the men from Aveiro|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=20 September 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> he appeared in 24 games and scored once in each of his two seasons in the [[Segunda Liga]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/desporto/benfica-empresta-seis-jogadores-ao-cd-fatima=f590319|title=Benfica empresta seis jogadores ao CD F\u00e1tima|trans-title=Benfica loan six players to CD F\u00e1tima|newspaper=[[Expresso (newspaper)|Expresso]]|language=Portuguese|date=25 June 2010|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> helping to a best-ever eighth place in [[2009\u201310 Liga de Honra|2009\u201310]].\n\nIn June 2011, Pereira opted to terminate his contract with Benfica and sign a two-year deal with Beira-Mar.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://semanal.omirante.pt/index.asp?idEdicao=503&id=75946&idSeccao=8231&Action=noticia#.Vv1QfkcjW1s|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira deixou o Benfica e assinou pelo Beira Mar|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira left Benfica and signed with Beira-Mar|newspaper=O Mirante|language=Portuguese|date=7 July 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/beira-mar-joao-pereira-ex-benfica-e-reforco|title=Beira Mar: Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Benfica) \u00e9 refor\u00e7o|trans-title=Beira-Mar: Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Benfica) is an addition|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=23 June 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> He would never appear for the team in a competitive game, being loaned the following month to [[C.D. Trofense]] also from the second division;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.noticiasdeaveiro.pt/pt/23050/beiramar-central-joao-pereira-vai-rodar-no-trofense/|title=Beira-Mar: Central Jo\u00e3o Pereira vai rodar no Trofense|trans-title=Beira-Mar: Stopper Jo\u00e3o Pereira will gain match experience in Trofense|newspaper=Not\u00edcias de Aveiro|language=Portuguese|date=30 August 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> in December, he agreed to a three-and-a-half-year deal with [[FC Sheriff Tiraspol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/joao-pereira-ex-beira-mar-no-fc-sheriff|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Beira Mar) no FC Sheriff|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira (ex-Beira Mar) in FC Sheriff|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisfutebol.iol.pt/beira-mar-confirma-joao-pereira-na-moldavia|title=Beira Mar confirma Jo\u00e3o Pereira na Mold\u00e1via|trans-title=Beira-Mar confirm Jo\u00e3o Pereira in Moldova|publisher=Mais Futebol|language=Portuguese|date=7 December 2011|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"UEFA\">{{cite web|url=http://pt.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=mda/news/newsid=1785353.html|title=Jovem Jo\u00e3o Pereira espera crescer no Sheriff|trans-title=Youngster Jo\u00e3o Pereira hopes to grow in Sheriff|publisher=UEFA|language=Portuguese|date=17 April 2012|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPereira made his [[Moldovan National Division]] debut on 3 March 2012, playing as [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|left back]] and providing an [[Assist (football)|assist]] in a 2\u20130 away win over [[FC Costuleni]],<ref name=\"UEFA\"/> and going on to contribute to the club's [[2011\u201312 Moldovan National Division|eleventh league title]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.publico.pt/noticia/mais-de-50-portugueses-conquistaram-trofeus-no-futebol-europeu-1548342|title=Mais de 50 portugueses conquistaram trof\u00e9us no futebol europeu|trans-title=Over 50 Portuguese won trophies in European football|newspaper=[[P\u00fablico (Portugal)|P\u00fablico]]|language=Portuguese|date=31 May 2012|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> He moved teams in countries again in January 2013, joining [[FC Nordsj\u00e6lland]] from [[Denmark]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://desporto.sapo.mz/futebol/internacional/artigo/2013/01/31/joao-pereira-vai-jogar-para-o-nordsjaelland|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira vai jogar para o Nordsjaelland|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira will play for Nordsjaelland|publisher=[[SAPO (company)|SAPO]]|language=Portuguese|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://expresso.sapo.pt/feeds/lusa/lusageral/joao-pereira-troca-moldavos-do-sheriff-pelos-dinamarqueses-do-nordsjaelland=f783635|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira troca moldavos do Sheriff pelos dinamarqueses do Nordsjaelland|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira swaps Moldova's Sheriff for Denmark's Nordsjaelland|newspaper=Expresso|language=Portuguese|date=31 January 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> after [[2012\u201313 Moldovan National Division|winning another league medal]] with Sheriff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ojogo.pt/internacional/portugueses/noticias/interior/joao-pereira-esta-na-dinamarca-mas-e-campeao-moldavo-3224514.html|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira est\u00e1 na Dinamarca mas \u00e9 campe\u00e3o moldavo|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira is in Denmark but is Moldovan champion|newspaper=[[O Jogo]]|language=Portuguese|date=16 May 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn late August 2013, after failing to receive any playing time, Pereira signed a six-month contract with [[Danish 1st Division|Danish second level]] club [[Vejle Boldklub|Vejle BK]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bt.dk/superligaen/vejle-henter-fc-nordsjaellands-kasserede-portugiser|title=Vejle henter FC Nordsj\u00e6llands kasserede portugiser|trans-title=Vejle sign discarded Portuguese from Nordsjaellands|newspaper=[[BT (tabloid)|BT]]|language=Danish|date=28 August 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> He extended his link in November for another six months,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagens.dk/fodbold/jo%C3%A3o-pereira-forl%C3%A6nger-med-vejle-boldklub|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira forl\u00e6nger med Vejle Boldklub|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira renews with Vejle Boldklub|newspaper=Dagens|language=Danish|date=12 November 2013|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> and again in April 2014 for another year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tipsbladet.dk/nyhed/1-division/vejle-forlaenger-med-joao-pereira|title=Vejle forl\u00e6nger med Jo\u00e3o Pereira|trans-title=Vejle renew with Jo\u00e3o Pereira|newspaper=Tipsbladet|language=Danish|date=1 April 2014|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Pereira moved to [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://desporto.sapo.pt/futebol/internacional/artigo/2015/06/26/joao-pereira-assina-pelos-dinamarqueses-do-sonderjyske|title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira assina pelos dinamarqueses do SonderjyskE|trans-title=Jo\u00e3o Pereira signs for Denmark's SonderjyskE|publisher=SAPO|language=Portuguese|date=26 June 2015|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> In January of the following year, website ''Bold'' announced that fellow [[Danish Superliga]] side [[Odense Boldklub]] had signed him for the [[2016\u201317 Danish Superliga|2016\u201317 campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bold.dk/fodbold/nyheder/ob-bekraefter-henter-joao-pereira/|title=OB bekr\u00e6fter: Henter Joao Pereira|trans-title=Odense deal: Jo\u00e3o Pereira acquired|publisher=Bold|language=Danish|date=26 January 2016|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nPereira earned 49 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]], across all youth levels. He played seven times for the [[Portugal national under-16 football team|under\u201316 team]], helping them win the Santar\u00e9m Tournament in February 2006<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-16-ganham-torneio-de-santarem.html|title=Sub-16 ganham Torneio de Santar\u00e9m|trans-title=Under-16 win Santar\u00e9m Tournament|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=28 February 2006|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> and finish seventh in the [[Montaigu Tournament]] in April;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-16-vitoria-sobre-a-china-a-fechar.html|title=Sub-16: Vit\u00f3ria sobre a China a fechar|trans-title=Under-16: Win over China to wrap it up|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=18 April 2006|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> later in the year, he participated in the Nike Tournament with [[Portugal national under-17 football team|the under\u201317s]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-17-portugal-perde-2-4-com-os-eua.html|title=Sub-17: Portugal perde (2\u20134) com os EUA|trans-title=Under-17: Portugal lose 2\u20134 with USA|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=11 September 2006|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> also competing in the Algarve International Tournament in February 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-17-portugal-em-ultimo.html|title=Sub-17: Portugal em \u00faltimo|trans-title=Under-17: Portugal in last place|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=20 February 2007|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPereira represented the [[Portugal national under-19 football team|under-19 team]] during the Ireland Tournament in August 2008,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-derrota-com-a-espanha.html|title=Sub-19: Derrota com a Espanha|trans-title=Under-19: Loss with Spain|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=19 August 2008|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> the La Manga Tournament in February 2009<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-selecao-nacional-conquista-la-manga.html|title=Sub-19: Sele\u00e7\u00e3o Nacional conquista La Manga|trans-title=Under-19: National team conquer La Manga|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=13 February 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> and the Porto Tournament in April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-portugal-vence-torneio-internacional-do-porto.html|title=Sub-19: Portugal vence Torneio Internacional do Porto|trans-title=Under-19: Portugal win Porto International Tournament|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=11 April 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref> Additionally, he played in the two qualifying rounds for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]], but the nation did not qualify.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/internacional/competicoes-de-selecoes/detalhe/sub-19-portugal-falha-europeu.html|title=Sub-19: Portugal falha Europeu|trans-title=Under-19: Portugal miss European Championship|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=28 May 2009|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nPereira first appeared with [[Portugal national under-21 football team|the under-21 side]] on 9 February 2011, starting in a 3\u20131 [[Exhibition game|friendly]] win over [[Sweden national under-21 football team|Sweden]] in his hometown.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/selecoes/detalhe/sub-21-portugal-bate-suecia-no-cartaxo-683329.html|title=Sub-21: Portugal bate Su\u00e9cia no Cartaxo|trans-title=Under-21: Portugal beat Sweden in Cartaxo|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=9 February 2011|accessdate=14 June 2016}}</ref> His only international goal arrived on 1 September of that year during a 2\u20130 success in [[Moldova national under-21 football team|Moldova]] for the [[2013 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification|2013 European Championship qualifiers]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/season=2013/matches/round=2000192/match=2006904/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Portugal prove too good for Moldova|publisher=UEFA|date=1 September 2011|accessdate=26 April 2016}}</ref> in which Portugal finished in second thus failing to progress to the finals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.record.xl.pt/futebol/selecoes/sub21/detalhe/avancado-do-v-guimaraes-ajuda-a-afastar-portugal-do-europeu-777549.html|title=Avan\u00e7ado do V. Guimar\u00e3es ajuda a afastar Portugal do Europeu|trans-title=V. Guimar\u00e3es forward helps oust Portugal from the European Championship|newspaper=Record|language=Portuguese|date=10 September 2012|accessdate=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 10 December 2017}}<ref>{{soccerway|joao-duarte-vieira-pereira/103235}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season